NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I think Nada might have come up with a different plan. Once Eddy leads a club, she can count 3 heart and 3 club tricks. So, all she has to do is take 2 trump tricks to make her contract. She should make sure they do not ruff out her winners. She does not need to trump anything on the board. So, if she just leads a low spade at trick 2, she can knock out the A and Q, and everything will work out easily. |
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Fortunately, she got some help from the defense. But the way she played it she would usually make 2 or perhaps even go down. Again, it comes down to counting your winners and coming up with a plan to take your winners. On opening lead, you should always look at all 4 suits to develop your plan.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let me remark on Eddy's opening lead. Leading away from an honor is a high risk lead. Typically I try to avoid leading away from honors, unless it is the only unbid suit or my partner has bid it. It could work out well. However, in general, given a suit I have an honor vs a suit with no honors, I tend to favor the suit with no honors.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The reason being, if declarer is taking a finesse in that suit, it is working anyway, so I am less likely to be giving something away. Eddy was a bit unlucky to be sure and I can construct many hands with the same auction where a club lead is right, and a diamond wrong. Opening leads are one of the least precise arts in bridge. So, all you can do is follow the odds and have a consistent set of rules as to what you do.|
